{{- /*  
    releaseryear.tmpl  
    This template is for the list of the releases organized by the first year of the earliest release.
    - Releaser  /releaser/year
    - Magazines /magazine
    -  "        /magazine/a-z
    - BBS       /bbs/year
*/ -}}
{{- define "content" }}
{{- $path := "g" }}
{{- $name := .itemName }}
{{- $pubs := index .stats.pubs }}
{{- $orderBy := index .stats.orderBy }}
{{- $class := "row row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-2 row-cols-md-3 g-2"}}
{{- $eraClass := "text-start text-secondary mx-5 mb-4"}}
<div class="container px-4 text-center">
    <p class="text-start lead"><small>Showing {{$pubs}}{{if ne $orderBy ""}}, ordered {{$orderBy | safeHTML}}{{end}}.</small></p>
{{- $prevYear := 0 }}
{{- range $index, $rel := .releasers -}}
    {{- $initialism := initialisms $rel.Unique.URI }}
    {{- $year := $rel.Unique.Year.Int }}
    {{- /* conditionals must always begin after these vars */ -}}
    {{ if eq $index 0}}
        {{- if and (gt $year 1981) (eq $index 0) }}<h3 class="text-end lead p-3"><span class="display-6">1981</span></h3>
        {{- else if (gt $year 0) }}<h3 class="text-end lead p-3"><span class="display-6">{{$year}}</span></h3>
        {{- end}}
        {{- if or (eq $year 1981) (and (eq $index 0) (gt $year 0)) }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Pre-Scene</em>.
The first IBM PC was released on 12 August 1981.
However, unlike today's worldwide releases, national same-day hardware launches were impossible, and the new machines trickled into US retailers over the following months.
At this time, piracy involved in-person meetings to copy and exchange software, and blank floppies were valuable commodities.
On the <a href="https://demozoo.org/productions/?platform=67&production_type=13&dir=asc&page=1">Apple II</a>, 
disk crackers had only begun tagging their work with handles in late 1980 while Scene groups and pirate bulletin boards became normalized in 1982.
</small></div>
        {{- if and (gt $year 1981) (eq $index 0) }}<h3 class="text-end lead p-3"><span class="display-6">{{$year}}</span></h3>{{end}}
        {{- end}}
        <div class="{{$class}}">
    {{- else}}
        {{- if and (gt $prevYear 0) (gt $year 0) (gt $year $prevYear) }}
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-end display-6 mt-3 p-3">{{$year}}</h3>
{{- if or (eq $year 1984) (eq $prevYear 1983)}}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">The local era</em>.
While 1983 saw the emergence of solo authors and the first public unprotect texts exchanging software cracking guides on commercial online services like CompuServe,
it was 1984 that marked the birth of the first PC Scene concept.
This period saw the formation of the first cracking collectives and groups, along with the sharing of software on local bulletin board systems.
These early PC groups were likely inspired by or emerged from the already-thriving Apple II Scene.
Meanwhile, the <a href="https://demozoo.org/productions/?platform=3&production_type=13&dir=asc&page=1">Commodore 64</a> was rapidly growing in popularity among young users in both the USA and Europe, fueling a rampant piracy scene.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1986 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Crackscreen fun</em>.
On the Apple II, purpose-drawn crack-title screens became widespread in 1984, while this practice didn't emerge on the PC until 1986.
Although bitmap drawing software was already well-established on the platform with programs like PC Paintbrush and PC Paint,
it likely took software hackers considerable time to develop ways to inject those images into cracked game titles.
Meanwhile, Sceners on more affordable platforms such as the Commodore 64 and <a href="https://demozoo.org/productions/?platform=9&production_type=4&dir=asc&page=1">Atari ST</a> were beginning to release animated cracktros
(cracked-by introductions) and intros with audio that attempted to replicate computer game title screens.
By contrast, the PC's fixed, 4-color CGA palette and silent static images appeared a little ugly and outdated.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1989 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">A national scene</em>.
1989 marked the emergence of a national PC Scene, as small local groups, often comprising just a few friends, 
teamed up with groups from other North American telephone area codes to form larger, more widespread cracking groups.
This period also saw the first proper cracktros and intros on the PC, though ironically these came from European users,
where the PC was least successful. Once again, the PC Scene lagged years behind the other microcomputers:
by this time the Apple II had passed its prime, the Commodore 64 and Atari ST were at their peaks,
and the Commodore Amiga was emerging as the best home-computer platform for gaming and multimedia.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1990 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Competition</em>.
This period saw the birth of the Art Scene, as amateur artists created text-based artwork and formed collectives, known as art groups,
focusing on designing advertisements and user interfaces for "elite" bulletin board systems.
The PC's extensive software catalog and backward compatibility made it the primary platform for affordable productivity applications and utilities,
a trend reflected in the software pirated for the platform. European pirate groups from the Commodore 64 and Amiga communities also began
exploring the PC, viewing it as a potential secondary system.
However, this era also marked the emergence of the modern cracking scene, with some groups competing to be first to crack and distribute new game releases.
While this practice was already commonplace on other microcomputer platforms, it was new to the laggard PC.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1991 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Silly names</em>.
1990 and 1991 witnessed a rise of excessively long group names, as various PC collectives, and those from the Commodore 64 and Amiga scenes, 
collaborated on PC releases. However, these groups were either too stubborn or egotistical to abandon their established identities.
Instead, they created absurdly long conjoined brand names for their PC releases. 
<em>Public Enemy / Tristar &amp; Red Sector / Defjam / The Dream Team present.</em>
<em>United Software Association and Fairlight PC Division proudly presents.</em>
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1992 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Drama</em>.
1992 marked the PC's rise as the dominant home-computing gaming platform.
While the PC remained a somewhat unusable platform, it had become clear that computer gaming's future lay with the open PC ecosystem,
which neither Apple, Commodore, nor Atari possessed the scale or resources to compete.
As the PC's popularity grew, so did its presence on "elite" bulletin board systems worldwide.
This surge in popularity led to a proliferation of scene magazines, often released as hard to read, multimedia presentations.
However, in late 1991 the PC piracy scene also faced its first major group schism due to personal conflicts,
followed by its first significant police raid in early 1992, which sent shockwaves through the community.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1993 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Peak demo</em>.
The demoscene originated with coders on other computer platforms who sought to recreate the impressive opening effects found in game title screens.
Initially intended to showcase their disk cracking abilities, it evolved into a competition to demonstrate programming prowess.
Unsurprisingly, the PC lagged behind this trend due to its many technical challenges.
However, it was on the PC in 1993 that demos arguably reached their peak with the release of "Second Reality" by Future Crew,
which briefly was the ultimate way for computer enthusiasts to demonstrate their hardware's capabilities.
But this was short-lived, as the following month saw the release of id Software's DOOM shareware edition,
which revolutionized the gaming world.
While the guys at Future Crew would go onto form Remedy Entertainment, <small>(Alan Wake and Max Payne fame)</small> 
whom in 1997 would release the Final Reality benchmark tool, a spiritual successor to the Demoscene release.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1994 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">The Internet@aol.com</em>.
Most networks, including the Internet, were closed systems requiring real-life qualifications for access,
typically through employment or education. This changed in 1991 when commercial Internet Service Providers were permitted to sell
business and home access to the network.
For Sceners in the mid-1990s, transitioning from bulletin boards with their limitations was an obvious choice, at least for real-time socializing.
However, the Internet was a time sink, had a steep learning curve, and compared to "elite" bulletin boards, lacked personality and even color.
Worse still, for the so-called "elite," it granted open access to what was formerly a somewhat private, underground Scene.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1995 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">End of the floppy</em>.
The mid-1990s brought massive changes to the PC landscape, including the rapid decline of floppy disk software distribution.
Within months, publishers abandoned floppies in favor of CD-ROM, creating numerous challenges for software cracking and distribution.
For some, this change meant the Cracking Scene was dead. To them, cracking software for the past 15-years had always meant breaking floppy disk copy protection.
1995 also saw the launch of Microsoft's Windows 95, the first widely adopted graphical operating system for the PC,
though hardcore gamers, and non-PC users remained unimpressed.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1996 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Pop Scene!</em>
The Scene's evolution mirrored social media's later rise and fall.
Many Sceners who gained status on closed "elite" bulletin boards found their newfound Internet celebrity irresistible -
often complaining publicly about "lamers" while also courting their attention and support.
1996 and 1997 represented the peak of Scene reporting, with high-profile interviews,
personality culture, and unprecedented open access.
Groups created websites such as razor1911.com as status symbols,
back when the Web 1.0 remained unmonetized, cryptic, bureaucratic, and expensive.
Some even sold branded merchandise, that they advertised in their releases, 
payable by mailing cash or a cheque to a PO Box, with the purchased wares shipped world-wide.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1997 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">ISO</em>
After years of incomplete and inconsistent CD rips-where cracking groups arbitrarily decided what to strip from games before distribution.
Some groups returned to releasing full games where they used CD copying software to generate complete disc images for online sharing.
While pirating entire CDs online wasn't new, there was no standard way until some adopted the ISO-9660 standard.
These full-disc images were unpopular with most users who were used to extremely limited bandwidth.
FTP site operators also disliked them because of their inherent size and the high costs of hosting such large files.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 1998 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">CD keys</em>
Game of the Year StarCraft from Blizzard Software introduces a user account system with its Battle.net online multiplayer service. 
Each account is tied to a unique serial number (CD key) included in the retail boxed copy of the game. 
Without a valid CD key, StarCraft cannot be used for multiplayer competitive gameplay, which is a core selling point. 
So, while the growing popularity of ISO releases allowed a return to sharing complete copies of pirated games, they were not always functionally identical to the retail software.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 2000 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Operation Cybercrime</em>
On May 4, 2000, the US Department of Justice announced that seventeen defendants from across the United States and Europe were indicted by a federal grand jury for 
allegedly conspiring to infringe the copyright of more than 5,000 computer software programs available through a hidden Internet site located at a university in Quebec, Canada. 
The group was Pirates With Attitude (PWA). Five of those indicted were Intel employees, and the file site was named Sentinel, which served as the group's
primary headquarters. The bust forced the closure of the nearly decade-old group and marked the first time someone was prosecuted for 'warez,' the sharing of software without profit.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 2001 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Operation Buccaneer</em>
A sequel of sorts occurred just 17 months after Operation Cybercrime, but this time the Department of Justice used the more playful name Operation Buccaneer and targeted PWA's longtime rivals, Drink or Die. 
Unlike the first operation, which failed to nab PWA members outside North America, Buccaneer involved about 70 search warrants across 17 countries and intended to send a message that playing anonymous online wasn't safe. 
The multinational takedown forced many to reevaluate their priorities and move on. 
Groups and sites downsized, went dark, or became minimal. 
The Scene forever changed; the days of publicly socializing, exchanging information, or engaging with user bases were over.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 2002 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">P2P</em>
Just as the Scene was veering further underground and reducing its size and exposure, piracy was exploding in the mainstream. Windows PCs and home Internet were booming, but it wasn't software piracy drawing attention—it was music, television, and
films. 2001 saw the peak and infamous takedown of Napster, the famed music 'sharing' platform, only for it to be replaced by a dozen clones by 2002. There was also the launch of BitTorrent, an Internet protocol enabling peer-to-peer file sharing,
eliminating the need for centralized file servers.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 2003 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><strong class="text-primary">☠️</strong>
While BitTorrent was a catch-all name, technically it was only a protocol—just like HTTP or FTP. A BitTorrent client couldn't do much without links to other clients sharing files. The Pirate Bay, launched in 2003, and similar websites provided an
easy, centralized, searchable repository of publicly available torrents on the Internet. Users could search for any song, album, game, film, or TV show and connect their BitTorrent software to others sharing the content they wanted. The irony was
that many in the PC piracy Scene despised this. As they retreated from the limelight, The Pirate Bay and its ilk exposed piracy to ever more people.
</small></div>
{{- else if eq $year 2004 }}
<div class="{{$eraClass}}">
<small><em class="text-primary">Steam</em>
2004 saw the first 'AAA' PC game released and distributed online, Half-Life 2 from Valve on their new digital distribution platform, Steam. 
Half-Life 2 was also released on CD and DVD at retail by a traditional publisher. 
But the online distribution allowed developers to earn more money and was often better for consumers, who didn't need to worry about out-of-stock or out-of-print games or deal with multi-disc installations from slow physical media. 
Over the years, Steam would eventually outweigh many advantages of PC game piracy, becoming an easier, faster, and more user-friendly distribution method than warez releases.
</small></div>
{{/* new entries goes here */}}
{{- end}}
            <div class="{{$class}}">
        {{- end}}
    {{- end}}
        <div class="col">
            <div class="p-3 border bg-light h-100 rounded-1"><h5><a href="/{{ $path }}/{{ $rel.Unique.URI }}">{{fmtURI $rel.Unique.URI}}</a></h5>
            <span class="text-muted">{{ $initialism }} &nbsp; </span>
            {{- byteFileS $name $rel.Unique.Count $rel.Unique.Bytes }}
            </div>
        </div>
{{- $prevYear = $year }}
{{- end}}
    </div>
</div>
{{- end }}
